    "It was his survey, <em>The Story of Art</em>, however, that established Gombrich's popular reputation.": [],
    "While most surveys had been little more than long lists of names, dates and discussions styles, Gombrich focused on the problems which artists at different periods had solved.": [],
    "Methodologically, he was particularly opposed to Marxist approaches to art (see Gombrich's discussion of the approach in the entry on <a href=\"/hausera\">Arnold Hauser</a>), Hegelian world views, or doctrines, such as <em>Weltanschauung</em> (Spirit of the Age\") that embraced cultural relativism or collectivizations of art.": [],
    "\"We should not go off on a tangent but rather learn as much as we can about the painter's craft,\" he declared.": [],
    "Gombrich was a charismatic lecturer, surprising audiences with images from magazine advertisements or Saul Steinberg cartoons in between projections of paintings of Old Masters.": [],
    "Not all of Gombrich's writings have wholly been accepted.": [],
    "His assertion of a link between Renaissance art and the philosophical doctrines, stated in the Botticelli Primavera article, have been doubted, even later by Gombrich himself, in the introduction to <em>Symbolic Images</em> (1972).": [],
    "He insisted that Hegel's work, not Winnckelmann's, should be considered the beginning of art history.": [
